it is known that the multiplicity of m exceeds m infinitely often for any
ford's theorem
proved that for every integer k there is a totient number m of multiplicity k that is for which the equation x m has exactly k solutions this result had previously been conjectured by wac aw sierpi ski and it had been obtained as a consequence of schinzel's hypothesis h indeed each multiplicity that occurs does so infinitely often
however no number m is known with multiplicity k carmichael's totient function conjecture is the statement that there is no such m
applications
cyclotomy
in the last section of the disquisitiones gauss proves that a regular n gon can be constructed with straightedge and compass if n is a power of if n is a power of an odd prime number the formula for the totient says its totient can be a power of two only if a n is a first power and b n is a power of the primes that are one more than a power of are called fermat primes and only five are known and fermat and gauss knew of these nobody has been able to prove whether there are any more
thus a regular n gon has a straightedge and compass construction if n is a product of distinct fermat primes and any power of the first few such n are
the rsa cryptosystem
setting up an rsa system involves choosing large prime numbers p and q computing n pq and k n and finding two numbers e and d such that ed mod k the numbers n and e the encryption key are released to the public and d the decryption key is kept private
a message represented by an integer m where m n is encrypted by computing s m e mod n
it is decrypted by computing t s d mod n euler's theorem can be used to show that if t n then t m
the security of an rsa system would be compromised if the number n could be factored or if n could be computed without factoring n
unsolved problems
lehmer's conjecture
if p is prime then p p in d h lehmer asked if there are any composite numbers n such that n n none are known
in he proved that if any such n exists it must be odd square free and divisible by at least seven primes i e n in cohen and hagis proved that n and that n further hagis showed that if divides n then n and n
carmichael's conjecture
this states that there is no number n with the property that for all other numbers m m n m n see ford's theorem above
as stated in the main article if there is a single counterexample to this conjecture there must be infinitely many counterexamples and the smallest one has at least ten billion digits in base
